<h2>Data Quality &amp; Definition</h2>
<h3>Definition of Famine</h3>
<p>According to Cormac √ì Gr√°da[ref]Cormac √ì Gr√°da (2009) ‚Äì Famine: A Short History. Princeton University Press. The book's website is <a href="http://press.princeton.edu/titles/8857.html">here</a>.[/ref] famine refers to 'a shortage of food or purchasing power that leads directly to excess mortality from starvation or hunger-induced diseases'. It is not always straightforward to distinguish it from malnutrition that is described in a <a title="Hunger and Undernourishment" href="http://ourworldindata.org/data/food-agriculture/hunger-and-undernourishment/">different entry in this website</a>. The distinguishing feature between malnutrition and a famine is the latter's crisis character.<br />
Generally a famine is more severe than malnutrition ‚Äì √ì Gr√°da is more specific in this respect and according to him a famine is characterised by 3 features:</p>
<ol>
<li>A 'daily death rate above 1 per 10.000 population',</li>
<li>The 'proportion of "wasted" children [that is, children weighing two standard deviations or more below the average] above 20 percent'[ref]Wasting is sometimes referred to as "acute malnutrition". <a href="http://conflict.lshtm.ac.uk/page_115.htm">The 'London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine' explains it <em>here</em></a>: 'wasting results from an acute shortage of food, is reversible with refeeding, and has a relatively high mortality rate'. This is different from stunting which is a chronic symptom of persistent malnutrition and less associated with food crises.[/ref]</li>
<li>'Prevalence of kwashiorkor' (extreme form of malnutrition mainly affecting young children).[ref]Kwashiorkor is explained <a href="http://conflict.lshtm.ac.uk/page_116.htm">here at the open-access educational resources for policy-makers provided by the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine</a>.[/ref]</li>
</ol>
<p>According to O Grada a 'severe famine' means</p>
<ol>
<li>A daily death rate of above 5 / 10.000,</li>
<li>A proportion of wasted children above 40 percent, and</li>
<li>Again, the prevalence of kwashiorkor.</li>
</ol>
<h3>Comparability Across Time</h3>
<p>In the study of famines of the past historical myopia is a severe problem.¬†Loveday, an early researcher of Indian famines, noted in 1914, "The frequency of the mention of famine in the later history . . . increases in exact proportion with the precision and accuracy in detail of her historians."[ref]Loveday (1914) page 10 as cited in √ì Gr√°da ‚Äì (2007).</p>
<p>Loveday (1914) ‚Äì Loveday, Alexander. 1914. The History and Economics of Indian Famines. Repr., New Delhi: Usha Publications, 1985.</p>
<p>√ì Gr√°da ‚Äì (2007) 'Famine: A Short History.' Princeton: Princeton University Press.[/ref]</p>
